HypothesisÂ¶

Universities can be grouped into distinct clusters based on their performance metrics (such as alumni employment, publications, faculty quality, and overall score). These clusters may reveal patterns of elite, mid-tier, and emerging universities.

4. Elbow MethodÂ¶

To determine the optimal number of clusters (k), I use the elbow method.
I plot the inertia (within-cluster sum of squares) for different values of k.

Handle Missing ValuesÂ¶

InÂ [30]:
# Drop rows with NaN in numeric columns
X = X.dropna()

# Scale again after dropping NaN
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

print("Shape after dropping NaN:", X.shape)

Shape after dropping NaN: (2000, 12)

Elbow Method to Determine Optimal kÂ¶

The elbow method was used to determine the optimal number of clusters. The "elbow" was observed at k=3, suggesting three meaningful clusters in the dataset

InÂ [84]:
inertia = []
K = range(1, 11)
for k in K:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)
    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6), dpi=150)
plt.plot(K, inertia, "o-", linewidth=2)
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters (k)", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("Inertia", fontsize=12)
plt.title("Elbow Method for Optimal k", fontsize=14, weight="bold")
plt.grid(True, linestyle="--", alpha=0.6)
plt.show()

Insight: The elbow point indicates the optimal number of clusters. Typically, a bend around k = 3 or k = 4 suggests a reasonable choice.

Why k=3?Â¶

Based on the elbow plot, the curve begins to flatten at k=3, which indicates diminishing returns when adding more clusters. Choosing 3 clusters provides a good balance between simplicity and capturing meaningful structure in the data.

InÂ [89]:
# 3. Fit KMeans ( k=3 as example)
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42, n_init=10)
cwur_df.loc[X.index, "cluster"] = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)

Interpreting the Elbow MethodÂ¶

The elbow method plot shows that inertia decreases rapidly at first and then starts to level off.
The "elbow" point appears around K=3, suggesting that three clusters provide the best balance between simplicity and performance.
This value of K was therefore chosen for the KMeans clustering analysis.

KMeans ClusteringÂ¶

Based on the elbow plot, Ä± select an appropriate number of clusters (k).
Here I choose k = 3 (this can be adjusted if the elbow suggests another value).

InÂ [33]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
InÂ [34]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# --- Select numeric columns ---
X = cwur_df[[
    "quality_of_education", "alumni_employment", "quality_of_faculty",
    "publications", "influence", "citations", "broad_impact", "patents", "score"
]]

# --- Drop rows with missing values ---
X = X.dropna()

# --- Standardize features ---
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)
InÂ [35]:
# --- Run KMeans ---
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42, n_init=10)
labels = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)

# --- Create a DataFrame with clustering results ---
cwur_clustered = cwur_df.loc[X.index].copy()
cwur_clustered["cluster"] = labels

cwur_clustered[["institution", "country", "score", "cluster"]].head()
Out[35]:

200 Harvard University USA 100.00 2
201 Stanford University USA 99.09 2
202 Massachusetts Institute of Technology USA 98.69 2
203 University of Cambridge United Kingdom 97.64 2
204 University of Oxford United Kingdom 97.51 2

Cluster Descriptive StatisticsÂ¶

The table above shows the average values of key metrics for each cluster.
From this, we can see that:

  • Cluster 0: Represents universities with relatively lower scores, publications, and citations.
  • Cluster 1: Represents medium-performing universities across most indicators.
  • Cluster 2: Represents top-performing universities with the highest averages across all indicators.

This confirms that the clustering effectively separates institutions into performance tiers.

Insights: Score vs. CitationsÂ¶

This plot shows the relationship between score and citations for universities.

  • Cluster 0 (red): Mid-scoring universities with high citation counts.
  • Cluster 1 (blue): Lower-scoring universities with fewer citations.
  • Cluster 2 (green): Elite universities with both the highest scores and citation counts.

Elite universities (Cluster 2) stand out clearly, showing strong performance across both overall scores and research impact.

Cluster Interpretation and Descriptive StatisticsÂ¶

The descriptive statistics reveal clear differences across clusters:

  • Cluster 0: Contains the elite universities. These institutions score very high across all indicators (score, citations, faculty quality, alumni employment).
  • Cluster 1: Represents mid-tier universities. Their performance is moderate, with balanced but not outstanding metrics.
  • Cluster 2: Emerging universities. They have lower scores on most dimensions, but may represent growing institutions with potential for improvement.

The scatterplot (Score vs. Citations) also supports this distinction, where universities naturally form three tiers: elite, mid-range, and developing.

This analysis confirms that clustering provides a meaningful segmentation of universities worldwide.

University Clusters (PCA 2D Projection)Â¶

InÂ [66]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

InÂ [68]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

pca = PCA(n_components=2)
pca_result = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

# Create columns in dataframe (only for rows without NaN)
cwur_df.loc[X.index, "pca1"] = pca_result[:, 0]
cwur_df.loc[X.index, "pca2"] = pca_result[:, 1]
InÂ [126]:
# --- 4. PCA for Visualization ---
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
pca_result = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

cwur_df.loc[X.index, "pca1"] = pca_result[:, 0]
cwur_df.loc[X.index, "pca2"] = pca_result[:, 1]

plt.figure(figsize=(12,8), dpi=150)
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

sns.scatterplot(
    x="pca1", y="pca2",
    hue="cluster",
    palette=sns.color_palette("Spectral", n_colors=3),
    data=cwur_df,
    s=70, edgecolor="black", alpha=0.7
)
plt.title("Clusters of Universities (PCA Projection)", fontsize=16, weight="bold")
plt.xlabel("Principal Component 1", fontsize=13)
plt.ylabel("Principal Component 2", fontsize=13)
plt.legend(title="Cluster", fontsize=12)
plt.show()

Insights: PCA Projection (Clusters of Universities)Â¶

This visualization shows how universities are grouped in a 2D space reduced by PCA from the original multi-dimensional dataset.

  • Cluster 0 (orange): Mid-performing universities, densely grouped in the center.
  • Cluster 1 (yellow): Lower-performing universities, more scattered.
  • Cluster 2 (green): Top-performing universities, clearly separated from the others.

This separation confirms that K-means clustering effectively distinguishes universities based on their performance levels.

7.Next StepsÂ¶

The clustering analysis highlights performance tiers across global universities.

Future research could include hierarchical clustering for comparison, analyzing changes in clusters over time, or integrating additional features (e.g., funding, international collaborations). This would provide deeper insights into global university performance patterns.

For future analysis:

  • Compare clusters across regions (e.g., Europe vs. Asia) to identify regional strengths.
  • Investigate additional variables such as funding levels, student demographics, or international collaborations to refine clusters.
  • Use clustering to track how universities move between groups over time.
  • Apply alternative clustering methods (e.g., hierarchical clustering or DBSCAN) to validate the robustness of the results.
